#Text=The two of you train together all the time ?
#Text=Pretty well , yes .
#Text=Yes , everything on snow basically is together .

#Text=One of the difficult things I guess is we have to have that 100 per cent communication and trust between one another and a lot of the female skiers on the circuit , their guide is their husband .
#Text=That 's kind of a trust relationship .
#Text=Eric does say that at times it feels like we 're married , but ...
#Text=I keep checking for my wallet .
#Text=... it 's always about constantly trying to continue to build that relationship so that eventually I just ...
#Text=You put your life in his hands and whatever he says , you do , kind of thing .
#Text=Of the two sport , winter sports and summer sports person , how do you find that balance between one sport and the other sport ?
#Text=It 's not easy .
#Text=Yeah , it 's not easy at all .
#Text=Yesterday was my first day on snow since March 16 , 2010 .
#Text=And that was mainly because of the build up obviously for London and the times when I was going to ski I was injured .
#Text=So , to not have skied for that long is obviously a huge disadvantage when all the girls have been racing the circuit since ... and it 's vice versa with track and field .
#Text=So I 've got an amazing team at the Victorian Institute of Sport .
#Text=I call them my little A Team of strength and mission coach , physio , osteopath , soft tissue therapist , sport psychologist , dietician .

#Text=Basically everyone has expertise in the area and we come together and having meetings and plan four years ahead and say at the moment Sochi 's the goal , but Rio 's still in the back of the head , and knowing my body so well now that I 've done both sports for five years means that I can know where they 've made mistakes , and I know where things have gone really well , so we can plan ahead for that and prepare so that the things that did go wrong wo n't happen again .
#Text=To make sure that I get to each competition in peak tone .
#Text=What things went wrong ?
#Text=Mainly injuries .
#Text=So , that 's the most difficult thing with doing two sports .
#Text=Track and field is an explosive power ; long jump and javelin are over four to six seconds of maximum effort .
#Text=Ski racing , you are on a course , for a minute to a minute and a half , so it 's a speed endurance event .
#Text=And the two could n't be further apart in terms of the capabilities and the capacities that you need as an athlete .

#Text=So one of the big things I guess , after the Vancouver campaign , being in ski boots for so long , I had lost a lot of muscle from my calves so they were n't actually firing properly , and when you 're trying to run and jump and you do n't have half of your leg working properly it makes it pretty difficult to jump a good distance .
#Text=Those kind of things .

#Text=So I 'm skiing now but when I 'm in a gym doing recovery and rehab or prehab stuff , I 've got calf raising , I 've got hamstring exercises because I know they 're the weaker areas that if I 'm not working on at the moment they 're two muscle groups that do n't get worked during ski .

#Text=That I need to do the extra stuff on the side so that when I transition back to track and field I do n't have any soft tissue injuries like strains because of the fact that I know they 're weaker so ...
